{{DISPLAYTITLE:Da Yu ''ding''}} {{Infobox artifact | name = Da Yu ''ding'' | native_name = 大盂鼎 | native_name_lang = zh | image = 大盂鼎 Da Yu ding.jpg | image2 = | image_caption = The Da Yu ''ding'' is exhibited in the [[National Museum of China]]. | material = [[Bronze]] | size = |height = {{convert|101.9|cm|adj=on}} |width = {{convert|77.8|cm|adj=on}} |weight = {{convert|153.5|kg|adj=on}} |long = | writing = | created = 1054 BC | discovered_place = Li Village, [[Mei County]], [[Shaanxi]] | discovered_coords = | discovered_date = 1849 | discovered_by = | location = [[National Museum of China]] | id = | map = | website = }} The '''Da Yu ''ding''''' ({{zh|c=大盂鼎|p=Dà Yú dǐng}}) is an ancient Chinese bronze circular ''ding'' vessel from the [[Western Zhou]] dynasty (1046&ndash;771 BC).{{sfnb|Qiu Xigui|2000|p=68}} Excavated in Li Village, [[Mei County]], [[Shaanxi]], it is on display in the [[National Museum of China]].{{sfnb|Li Song|2015|p=30}}
The Da Yu ''ding'', the [[Da Ke ding|Da Ke ''ding'']] in the [[Shanghai Museum]], and the [[Mao Gong Ding|Mao Gong ''ding'']] in the [[National Palace Museum]] in [[Taipei]] are famous bronze dings.
==Description== The tripod is round, with three legs, a common shape during the Western Zhou dynasty. It is {{convert|101.9|cm|adj=on}} high and weighs {{convert|153.5|kg}}. Its aperture is {{convert|77.8|cm|adj=on}}. Its mouth was engraved with [[Taotie]] patterns and its four legs was engraved with animal face patterns. The king is attributed to [[King Kang of Zhou]] (1020&ndash;996 BC), and the date is attributed to the 23rd Year of the king, the [[Western Zhou|Western Zhou dynasty]](1046&ndash;771 BC) <ref>Shanghai Museum 1959</ref>
==Inscription== [[File:Da Yu ding inscription.jpg|thumb|Inscription inside the Da Yu ''ding'']] The tripod has 291 Chinese characters in 19 lines inside the tripod<ref>Da yu Ding Chinese Rubbing Collection Harvard University, USA WEBsite</ref>. Most is The King's Speech. 1st speech is a Historical Overview in which he provides a moral rationale for the fall of the [[Shang dynasty]] (c. 1600&ndash;1046 BC) and the rise of the Western Zhou. Here, the King said that the excess of drinking wine made Yin dynasty had lost the heaven grace and army. And the Kings of Zhou have not excess drinking in even ceremonial scenes. And, the King commands Yu({{zh|s=盂|t=|labels=no}}). support the King, and work official service throughout days. The 2nd is a short charge to Yu to emulate his late grandfather, Nang Gong. The 3rd is the appointment of king's minister with army power. And the detailed inventory granted by the King. At last, Yu himself recorded that he made this tripod for his deceased grandfather Nang Gong in response to the kings kindness. It was the king's 23th year<ref> Jeffrey R. Thersen 2015 103-127p </ref><ref> Robert Eno, Indiana University Document</ref>. The 1726 slaves in the inventory, is an important historic material for studying slavery.
==History== [[File:Zuo Zongtang 1875.jpg|thumb|130px|right|[[Zuo Zongtang]] (1812&ndash;1885), the fifth ower of the Da Yu ''ding'']] [[File:潘祖蔭.jpg|thumb|130px|right|[[Pan Zuyin]] (1830&ndash;1890), the sixth ower of the Da Yu ''ding'']] In the [[Daoguang Emperor|Daoguang era]] (1821&ndash;1851) of the [[Qing dynasty]] (1644&ndash;1911), this tripod was unearthed in Li village, [[Mei County, Shaanxi]]. Song Jinjian ({{zh|s=宋金鉴|t=宋金鑒|labels=no}}; 1821&ndash;1863), a local rich man, acquired it. Next, the governnor Zhou Gengsheng ({{zh|s=周庚盛|t=|labels=no}}) expropriated it. After he died, Song Jinjian recovered the tripod <ref> record in Shaanxi Epigraphy({{zh|s= |t=陕西金石志, 1934|labels=no}}) in Shanghai Museum 1959. Another record showed the owner another Ko family. there is controversy</ref>.
Before 1873 winter, Yuan Baoheng ({{zh|s=袁保恒|t=|labels=no}}; 1826&ndash;1878), a follower of [[Zuo Zongtang]] bought it at a price of 700 tael of silver<ref>Wu Dacheng(1835-1902) appreciated and recorded the tripod in Yuan's estate in Shaanxi in 1873 winter. </ref>. Yuan might send the tripod he bought to Zuo Zongtang. In 1875<ref>On the letter at 1875 March ([[Guangxu Emperor]] era 1st year January(Chinese calendar) 11th) from Chen Jieqi(1813-1884) to Pan Zuyin </ref>, Zuo Zongtang presented the tripod he treasured as a gift to [[Pan Zuyin]](({{zh|s=潘祖荫|t=潘祖蔭|labels=no}};; 1830&ndash;1890) in Beijing<ref>Shanghai Museum 1959 </ref>. Pan Zuyin was a famous collector with rich knowledge in [[Chinese characters]]. In 1890, Pan acquired the [[Da Ke ding|Da Ke ''ding'']], the second largest bronzeware of the Western Zhou dynasty after the Da Yu ''ding''. His younger brother Pan Zunian ({{zh|s=潘祖年|t=|labels=no}}; 1870&ndash;1925) inherited the family property. In about 1896, Pan Family moved to [[Suzhou]] from Beijing with their collection including two tripods.
In 1937, the Second Sino-Japanese War broke out. Fearing looting or destruction, Pan family packed the two tripods in a wood box and buried it in the earth.
In 1951, Pan Dayu({{zh|s=潘达于|t=潘達于|labels=no}}; 1906&ndash;2007) donated the two tripod to the nation. <ref>Pan Dayu wrote a short letter, intending to donate the two tripods to Shanghai Museum. A few months later, Liu Ruli ({{zh|s=刘汝醴|t=劉汝醴|labels=no}}) and Shen Gengmei ({{zh|s=沈羹梅|t=|labels=no}}) went to Suzhou accompanied by Pan Jiahua ({{zh|s=潘家华|t=潘家華|labels=no}}), daughter of Pan Dayu, to take the tripods. Mao Dun (1896–1981), the Minister of Culture, personally inscribed an honorary credential for her.</ref> Shanghai Museum displayed the two tripods and published <ref>Shanghai Museum 1959 </ref>. In 1959, the Da Yu ''ding'' was transferred to Beijing and became one of the most valuable treasure in [[National Museum of China]]. In March 2004, in order to celebrate Pan Dayu's 100 birthday, the Da Yu ''ding'' was transferred to Shanghai Museum for a special and short display. It's their reunion for half a century.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://news.sina.com.cn/o/2004-03-02/04001937654s.shtml |script-title=zh:大克鼎和大盂鼎：半世纪后再聚首|trans-title=Da Yu ''ding'' and Da Ke ''ding'': reunited after half a century |newspaper=sina |date=2004-03-02 |language=zh}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author= |url=https://news.qq.com/a/20040229/000200.htm |script-title=zh:国宝级文物大盂鼎大克鼎五十年后上海相聚|trans-title=National treasures the Da Yu ''ding'' and Da Ke ''ding'' are reunited half a century later in Shanghai |newspaper=Tencent |date=2004-02-09 |language=zh}}</ref>
