{{about|the carnival character found in Caribbean |the play by [[Steve Carter (playwright)|steve carter]]|Dame Lorraine (play)}}
{{refimprove|date=September 2016}}
'''Dame Lorraine''' ([[Trinidad and Tobago]])as it is called in the land of its birth [[Trinidad]], and in the wider diaspora, or ''Mother Sally'' in Barbados, is a historical Trinidad [[Carnival Character]].<ref>[http://www.tntislandh.com/carnivalcharacters.html "Dame Lorraine or Dame Lorine"], Traditional Carnival Characters.</ref> She is characterized as a voluptuously large woman who wears a long dress and dances in the mas. According to the Trinidad and Tobago National Library, the character is "imitative of the mas played by the 18th and early 19th century French planters, who would dress up in elegant costumes of the French aristocracy and parade in groups at private homes, particularly on Carnival Sunday night. They also performed the sophisticated dances of the period. The liberated slaves recreated these costumes – complete with elaborate fans and hats – in their own fashion, using materials that were readily available, such as assorted rags and imitation jewellery-type items, but emphasizing and exaggerating the physical characteristics, and dancing to small bandol and cuatro bands. they also put pillows or stuffings to make their behind and bosoms bigger".<ref>[http://www.nalis.gov.tt/Research/SubjectGuide/Carnival/tabid/105/Default.aspx?PageContentID=81 "Traditional Carnival Characters"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141215172237/http://www.nalis.gov.tt/Research/SubjectGuide/Carnival/tabid/105/Default.aspx?PageContentID=81 |date=2014-12-15 }}, NALIS.</ref> Whereas in the past it was mainly men who dressed as the Dame Lorraine character, lately more women portray the character.<ref>[http://www.ncctt.org/new/index.php/carnival-history/trad-carnival-characters/317-traditional-mas-characters-dame-lorraine.html "Traditional Mas Characters - Dame Lorraine"], National Carnival Commission of Trinidad and Tobago.</ref>

