'''Ernst Waldschmidt''' (July 15, 1897, [[Lünen]], [[Province of Westphalia]] – February 25, 1985, [[Göttingen]]) was a [[German people|German]] [[oriental studies|orientalist]] and [[Indologist]]. He was a pupil of German indologist [[Emil Sieg]].
He taught at [[Berlin University]] and began teaching at the [[University of Göttingen]] in 1936. Waldschmidt joined the [[Nazi|Nazi party]] in May 1937.<ref>Anikó Szabó: Vertreibung, Rückkehr, Wiedergutmachung - Göttinger Hochschullehrer im Schatten des Nationalsozialismus'', 2000</ref>
He was a specialist on [[Indian philosophy]], and archaeology of [[India]] and [[Central Asia]]. He also founded Stiftung Ernst Waldschmidt.
== Literary works == * ''Buddhistische Kunst in Indien'', 1932 * ''Die buddhistische Spätantike in Mittelasien'' (the 7th Volume), 1933 * ''Gandhara, Kutscha, Turfan'', 1925 * ''Die Überlieferung vom Lebensende des Buddha'', 2 Vols., 1944-1948
