'''Helen Damico''' is a scholar of [[Old English]] and [[Old English literature]]. She received her Ph.D. from [[New York University]] in 1980, and is a professor emerita at the [[University of New Mexico]], where she began teaching in 1981 and founded the Institute for Medieval Studies. The author of ''Beowulf's Wealhtheow and the Valkyrie Tradition'', Damico has made important contributions to the study of women in Old English and Old Norse literature, and her work on [[Wealhþeow]] is frequently cited.<ref>{{cite book|last=Carruthers|first=Leo|editor=Leo Carruthers|others=Raeleen Chai-Elsholz, Tatjana Silec|title=Palimpsests and the Literary Imagination of Medieval England: Collected Essays|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=favIAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA154|year=2011|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=9780230118805|pages=139–56|chapter=Rewriting Genres: ''Beowulf'' as Epic Romance}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Hill|first=John M|title=Narrative Pulse of Beowulf: Arrivals and Departures|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H3g9cCr7924C&pg=PT65|year=2009|publisher=U of Toronto P|isbn=9781442691940|page=65}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Chickering|first=Howell|year=2009|title=Poetic Exuberance in the Old English ''Judith''|journal=[[Studies in Philology]]|volume=106|issue=2|pages=119–36|jstor=25656006}}</ref> She saw representations of the [[valkyrie]] in both Wealhþeow and [[Grendel's Mother]] Damico sees in the [[Old English literature|Old English poem]] ''[[Beowulf]]'' (c. 700–1000 AD).<ref name="Fugelso2010">{{cite book|last=Marshall|first=David W.|editor=Karl Fugelso|title=Defining Neomedievalism(s)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JiX109CDWUcC&pg=PA136|accessdate=17 February 2015|year=2010|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=9781843842286|pages=135–59|chapter=Getting Reel with Grendel's Mother: Abject Maternal and Social Critique}}</ref>
