{{Infobox book | italic title = <!--(see above)--> | name = The Shadow of the Sun | image = The Shadow of the Sun - R. Kapuscinski.jpg | image_size = 220px | alt = | caption = Front cover of ''The Shadow of the Sun'' by [[Ryszard Kapuściński]] | author = [[Ryszard Kapuściński]] | translator = Klara Glowczewska | illustrator = | publisher = [[Penguin Books]] | pub_date = 2001 | isbn = | isbn_note = | oclc = | website = }} '''''The Shadow of the Sun''''' ({{lang-pl|Heban}}, literally "Ebony") is a [[Travel literature|travel memoir]] by the Polish writer and journalist [[Ryszard Kapuściński]]. It was published by [[Penguin Books]] in 2001 with the English translation by Klara Glowczewska. Kapuściński spent nearly 30 years in various African countries such as [[Kenya]], [[Rwanda]], [[Nigeria]], [[Ethiopia]] and more, detailing his accounts as a white, foreign visitor, of the development of the African states.<ref name=Dyer/>
Kapuściński's experience in Africa was unique, because he had the opportunity to stay with people of various classes in society, staying with ministers, as well as peasants in rural villages which gave him an honest perspective on what was the current situation of the continent.<ref name=Ryle>John Ryle (2001), "At play in the bush of ghosts" originally published as the “Tales of Mythical Africa” by the ''Times Literary Supplement'', 27 July 2001. Review of: Ryszard Kapuściński, ''The Shadow of the Sun'', translated by Klara Glowczewska, 336 pp, [[Penguin Books]], 2001. See: [http://www.richardwebster.net/johnryle.html Reprint of the review in full.]</ref> {{quote|The early pages of ''The Shadow of the Sun'', a compendium of further adventures in Africa, find [[Ryszard Kapuściński]] in [[Dar es Salaam]] in 1962, where he hears that [[Uganda]] is about to gain independence. He and a friend, Leo, promptly set off for [[Kampala]] via the [[Serengeti]], with its teeming wildlife. "It's all improbable, incredible. As if one were witnessing the birth of the world, that precise moment when the earth and sky already exist, as do water, plants, and wild animals, but not yet Adam and Eve." They have no maps, they're lost, and they're confronted with an enormous herd – "stretching almost to the horizon" – of buffalo. They press on regardless.<ref name=Dyer>Geoff Dyer (2 June 2001), [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2001/jun/02/politics Book review: ''The Shadow of the Sun'' by Ryszard Kapuscinski, trans. Klara Glowczewska, Penguin, 336 pp.] The Guardian.</ref>}}
